{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5ba8d77f-ce06-40ec-a75d-e334b0c8e8a1","content":"The project uses MSTest 3.8 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me restore and run the tests with TRX reporting.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01ThcY4Qtq2JcKpn5G9HPzU6","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-3482d973a76044629da1689359854228 && dotnet restore --verbosity quiet 2>&1 && dotnet test --report-trx 2>&1","description":"Restore and run tests with TRX report","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Restore and run tests with TRX report"}],"interactionId":"1a4df2f4-e779-4bc4-bff0-586a94b73b34","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest 3.8.0 with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`). To produce a TRX report with `dotnet test`, I need to pass the appropriate arguments.\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform and `dotnet test`, TRX reporting requires the `--report-trx` flag (since MSTest 3.x uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively). But let me check - with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` set to true, `dotnet test` delegates to the testing platform. The TRX report can be generated via `--report-trx`.\n \nI'm realizing there are two possible approaches here. With `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport=true`, `dotnet test` forwards arguments to the testing platform, so `--report-trx` should work. Alternatively, the traditional VSTest logger syntax `--logger trx` might also be supported, though that's the older approach.\n\nLet me just run the tests and see what happens. First I need to restore the project.","outputTokens":512,"requestId":"480C:72329:327CF6C:372F9F0:69FBE690"},"id":"0ec24f6a-5e69-4771-bb89-58bf159f9bac","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:10:51.200Z","parentId":"f7203bbc-8ada-49b5-8fbf-fcfa887f8990"}
